          My first name, which I share with my father and grandfather, is
          indigenous to Brazil. It is pronounced exactly like it is written, but [here is Moacir Santos](https://youtu.be/_CWapwtGsaE?t=38s) saying it, [here is Vinicius de Moraes](https://youtu.be/KEAxP_B2wcM?t=5m14s) saying it, and [here Flávio Alcaraz Gomes](https://youtu.be/VgVUAo2gXv0?t=25s) says it while interviewing author Moacyr Scliar (he repeats it again at :30 when asking into how many languages Scliar’s work has been translated).
          
          The etymology of the name is asserted in the *[Vocabulário
          tupi-guarani
          português](http://www.worldcat.org/title/vocabulario-tupi-guarani-portugues/oclc/9234037)*
          as:
          
          > **Mboací** — v. tr. Fazer doer, provocar dores, maguar, ofender, ferir. Daqui vem **moaci** que passou a prenome sob a forma **Moacir**.
          >
          > […]
          >  
          > **Moacyr** — adj. Aquele que causa dores, que molesta, o doloroso. Prenome masculino. [[machine translation](http://translate.google.com/#pt|en|%20%20%20%20Mboac%C3%AD%20%E2%80%94%20v.%20tr.%20Fazer%20doer%2C%20provocar%20dores%2C%20maguar%2C%20ofender%2C%20ferir.%20Daqui%20vem%20moaci%20que%20passou%20a%20prenome%20sob%20a%20forma%20Moacir.%0A%0A%20%20%20%20[%E2%80%A6]%0A%0A%20%20%20%20Moacyr%20%E2%80%94%20adj.%20Aquele%20que%20causa%20dores%2C%20que%20molesta%2C%20o%20doloroso.%20Prenome%20masculino.)]

          The name also has a literary history, as it is the name given to the
          son in the 1865 Brazilian novel
          *[Iracema](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iracema)*. The son is a
          talisman of a promise to a mixed Brazilian culture, expressed
          racially by blending indigenous and European blood:
            
          > [Iracema, sentindo que se lhe rompia o seio](http://books.google.com.br/books?id=MEbKsiomE2QC&amp;pg=PA148&amp;dq=%22Iracema,+sentindo+que+se+lhe+rompia+o+seio%22&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=wd7xTf7kCMKp8AP2063zAw&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;ct=result&amp;resnum=1&amp;ved=0CCcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&amp;q=%22Iracema%2C%20sentindo%20que%20se%20lhe%20rompia%20o%20seio%22&amp;f=false), buscou a margem do rio, onde crescia o coqueiro.
          >
          > Estreitou-se com a haste da palmeira. A dor lacerou suas entranhas; porém logo o choro infantil inundou sua alma de júbilo.
          >
          > A jovem mãe, orgulhosa de tanta ventura, tomou o tenro filho nos braços e com ele arrojou-se às aguas limpidas do rio. Depois suspendeu-o à teta mimosa; seus olhos então o envolviam de tristeza e amor.
          >
          > — Tu és Moacir, o nascido de meu sofrimento.
          >
          > A ará, pousada no olho do coqueiro, repetiu Moacir; e desde então a ave amiga unia em seu canto ao nome da mãe, o nome do filho. [[machine translation](http://translate.google.com/#pt|en|%20%20%20%20Iracema%2C%20sentindo%20que%20se%20lhe%20rompia%20o%20seio%2C%20buscou%20a%20margem%20do%20rio%2C%20onde%20crescia%20o%20coqueiro.%0A%0A%20%20%20%20Estreitou-se%20com%20a%20haste%20da%20palmeira.%20A%20dor%20lacerou%20suas%20entranhas%3B%20por%C3%A9m%20logo%20o%20choro%20infantil%20inundou%20sua%20alma%20de%20j%C3%BAbilo.%0A%0A%20%20%20%20A%20jovem%20m%C3%A3e%2C%20orgulhosa%20de%20tanta%20ventura%2C%20tomou%20o%20tenro%20filho%20nos%20bra%C3%A7os%20e%20com%20ele%20arrojou-se%20%C3%A0s%20aguas%20limpidas%20do%20rio.%20Depois%20suspendeu-o%20%C3%A0%20teta%20mimosa%3B%20seus%20olhos%20ent%C3%A3o%20o%20envolviam%20de%20tristeza%20e%20amor.%0A%0A%20%20%20%20%E2%80%94%20Tu%20%C3%A9s%20Moacir%2C%20o%20nascido%20de%20meu%20sofrimento.%0A%0A%20%20%20%20A%20ar%C3%A1%2C%20pousada%20no%20olho%20do%20coqueiro%2C%20repetiu%20Moacir%3B%20e%20desde%20ent%C3%A3o%20a%20ave%20amiga%20unia%20em%20seu%20canto%20ao%20nome%20da%20m%C3%A3e%2C%20o%20nome%20do%20filho.)]

          The baby’s name is translated in the recent [LoLA
          edition](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0195115481/ref=sib_vae_dp/102-3411003-0229768?%5Fencoding=UTF8&amp;no=283155&amp;me=ATVPDKIKX0DER&amp;st=books)
          as “[Child of
          suffering](http://www.amazon.com/gp/reader/0195115481/ref=sib_vae_pg_16/102-3411003-0229768?_encoding=UTF8&amp;keywords=Moacir&amp;p=S04F&amp;twc=5&amp;checkSum=zES7HgPVMiJouubcucEuL1vjqdlbENchndYFsHd3Esk%3D#reader-link).”
          It is unclear what or who is *causing* the suffering. To my ears,
          “Child of suffering” suggests that the baby is not related to
          creating the pain. The above definition of “Moacyr” invalidates that
          reading. In the Foreword to the LoLA edition, Lindstrom shows how the
          mother, Iracema, [suffers after giving
          birth](http://www.amazon.com/gp/reader/0195115481/ref=sib_vae_pg_16/102-3411003-0229768?%5Fencoding=UTF8&amp;keywords=Moacir&amp;p=S04F&amp;twc=5&amp;checkSum=zES7HgPVMiJouubcucEuL1vjqdlbENchndYFsHd3Esk%3D#reader-link),
          but that suffering is interpreted as emblematic of the insufficiency
          of the native population to maintain Brazil. The son, then, is not
          the cause of the suffering, but the promissory note of a brilliant,
          mixed future. On the other hand, he is, still, causing the suffering
          by representing a surrender of the indigenous racial (and cultural)
          past to the Portuguese colonizers. Let’s not even get started on how
          ludicrous it is to speak of Brazilian culture by using only the
          Indians and Portuguese as points of references—even in 1865.
            
